<br>
Show for certain that the technical problems with the GCNR can be solved as easily as the 'problems' with Orion: A supply of weapons-grade fissionables and steel.<br>
<br>
Yeah, yeah, poke fun at Orion for sounding like a 4th grader's idea for a ship. Prove that there's something as good and simple as it.<br>
Riding the shock wave from nuclear blasts is just the best we can do without some real breakthroughs. [/qoute]<br>
<br>
It does sound like something a 4th grader would come up with, actually... <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :rollin --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/roll.gif ALT=":rollin"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
For a heavy lift system, it has everything beat, hands down. <br>
A 1 kg mass of plutonium, used to fuel a GCNR engine would last longer. If used to make a nuclear device, I would guess about 70-90% of the plasma shockwave would be lost without impinging on the pusher plate. <br>
That is if the pusher plate would even survive the explosion. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=megaloman84>Megaloman84</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 6<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/22/03 5:59 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=301.topic&index=23>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/nimoy.gif" align=absmiddle>  Seriously folks</span><hr size=1> I find it hard to believe that Orion-type craft are still occupying noticeable amounts of people's time.<br>
<br>
In the 50 years since the idea was conceived, many better ones have been concocted.<br>
<br>
True, we could build an Orion now, unlike most other concepts.  But we have already achieved scientific breakeven in controlled fusion reactors.  This technology should be available within a few short decades and would enable the use of fusion plasma drives of much greater efficiency and controllability.  A magnetic nozzle could harness the energy of a controlled fusion reaction much more effectively than a plate can tap the force of an explosion.  <br>
<br>
Even a Deadalus-type starship, while basically the same  as an Orion in principle, would be much better.<br>
<br>
Both of these technologies would enable acceleration at rates greatly less than 33.5Gs, an absolute necessity for crew comfort. Yes I am aware that you intend to use springs to absorb and dissipate the force over a longer time period and create a reduction in felt acceleration, but I am unsure how you intend to do so to the massive extent required. <br>
<br>
Even more promising, carbon catalyzed proton-proton fusion utilizing the CNO cycle is only about 1,000,000 more difficult than the D-D, D-T and D-He3 that we are currently on the threshold of developing.  This would enable practical Bussard ramjets to be constructed.<br>
<br>
This is significantly more difficult, but I feel confident that it can be done eventually.<br>
<br>
Nevertheless, the fact remains that we are nearing the point where controlled fusion is within our grasp.  This is a technology that lends itself to far superior propulsion mechanisms than Orion-type drives.<br>
<br>
Since we will have our hands full exploring and developing just our own solar system for quite a while, I think we can postpone interstellar exploration for a few decades until we can do it right.<br>
