just saying that the resources that we could use to build an Orion would be better spent addressing near term space goals, like putting colonies on the moon, Mars, and in the asteroid belt.<br>
<br>
Plus, I think the Orion concept has a number of serious shortcomings.  Not the least of which is that a ship of the size you are talking about would have to be launched from the surface of the earth. Building one in orbit with present technology would be hideously expensive.  I am not really too keen on the idea of detonating large numbers of H-bombs in the earth's atmosphere, despite my otherwise strong support for space nuclear power and propulsion.<br>
<br>
With the established space infrastructure that will enable our children to build large structures in space out of materials mined from asteroids, I would have no problem with the construction of an Orion, if such an undertaking was still deemed worthwhile despite technological improvement.  But I happen to think that launching one from earth would be reckless and irresponsible.<br>
<br>
I was mainly just pointing out that there are a lot of vastly more elegant and efficient propulsion schemes that are just around the corner, and we can easily afford to pursue other objectives while they mature. <br>
<br>
There is plenty of space right here in our backyard, and technologies such as VTOL SSTOs, NEP and NTR, that do not have the kind of stigma, pollution or risk as Orion can open it up quickly and affordably.  <br>
<br>
The stars will still be waiting for us when the next generation of pioneers set their sights on them from their homes on Mars, on the asteroids, and in the outer solar system.  Plus, the technology available to them will enable them to colonize the nearby stars without having to resort to muti-generational ark ships or suspended animation.<br>
<br>
I simply don't think humanity is ready to reach for the stars at this point in time.  However, I have never advocated complacency or stagnation.    <br>
