<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.nuclearspace.net/hotrod.htm"><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/images/hotrod.jpg"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :eek --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/eek.gif ALT=":eek"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
This older article is a good intro<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.islandone.org/Propulsion/ProjectOrion.html">www.islandone.org/Propulsion/ProjectOrion.html</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
and a newer look<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.nuclearspace.com/a_orion_and_empire.htm">www.nuclearspace.com/a_orion_and_empire.htm</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
The men who thought up ORION did not make rockets, they built bombs. ORION was based on the seemingly ludicrous idea of using nuclear bombs to propel a ship. ORION used specially designed directional bombs to ionize propellant and push it back towards the ship. The ship would carry a large plate, known as the pusher, with which to catch the propellant. Shock absorbers would reduce the force felt by the crew to survivable levels. The use of high energy nuclear fuel gave the system a high Isp, while the tremendous force generated by the bomb's plasma produced high thrust. Most propulsion systems offer high thrust, like a chemical rocket, or high Isp, like an ion thruster, but not both at the same time. This was one of the many advantages of ORION.<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.nuclearspace.com/article/orion_and_empire_files/image017.gif"><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/article/orion_and_empire_files/image018.gif"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=johnfraz>John Fraz</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_yingyang.gif" BORDER=0> at: 2/27/03 11:04:37 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=megaloman84>Megaloman84</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 24<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/27/03 11:27 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=301.topic&index=40>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/fry1.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Orion</span><hr size=1> It seems I too must admit ignorance.  I didn't realize that someone had developed directional nuclear bombs.  Still seems a bit crude, but now my only objection to using an Orion in low orbit would have to be the threat of electro-magnetic pulse.  It should be easy to minimize the damage by only firing pulses above uninhabited areas.   <br>
<br>
This could be accomplished by sending the Orion into a polar orbit and only firing pus' above the north pole (there are manned bases in Antarctica, so the south pole might not work.)<br>
<br>
Firing could increase in frequency once sufficient distance from earth was reached.<br>
<br>
However, you will have a hard time convincing me of the necessity and safety of a ground launched Orion.<br>
<br>
Overall, I still prefer the NSWR.  I think the technology lends itself to higher performance, plus it's safer and could be used without heavy and bulky shock absorbers, further increasing performance.  Just my personal preference.    <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <table border=0 width=95%><tr><td align=left valign="top">  Page <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showMessageRange?topicID=301.topic&start=1&stop=20>1</a> <b>2</b> <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showMessageRange?topicID=301.topic&start=41&stop=43>3</a> </td><td align=right valign="top"><a href="http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showPrevMessage?topicID=301.topic"> << Prev Topic</a>&nbsp;| <a href="http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showNextMessage?topicID=301.topic"> Next Topic >> </a><br><br><a self href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=301.topic&index=40><img src=http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/addreply3.jpg border=0 alt="Add Reply"></a> </td></tr></table><br><table width=95% border=0><td valign="top"> <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.emailToFriend?topicID=301.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/image/email.gif border=0 alt="Email This To a Friend"> Email This To a Friend</a><br> <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.threadControl?topicID=301.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/space/deleteThread.gif border=0 alt="Topic Control Image"> Topic Commands</a><br> <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.subscribeUnregisteredToTopic?topicID=301.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/ultimate/subscribe.gif width=20 height=20 border=0 alt="Click to receive email notification of replies"> Click to receive email notification of replies</a> <br>  <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.unsubscribeUnregisteredToTopic?topicID=301.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/theme